European Defense and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, the Nazi occupation.
Perhaps it is due to the experience of living in a country in the heart of Europe, a place that has been a crossing point of the intellectual streams, geopolitical interests, and confrontations of Europe for centuries.
Maybe all these factors combined have led me to the conviction that Europe represents a single political entity, whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could be two Europes forever - one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, and one less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated - is an illusion.
That is like heating up a part of a room while it stays cold in the other part.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event sends an echo across Europe.
If Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to admit the new post-communist democracies – which is in Europe's interest –, a series of essential tasks must be tackled, both within the new democracies and within the European and the Atlantic communities.
First, Europe must promote community in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
For a living society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe must therefore help its new democracies to become an organic part of a shared continental commitment to deepen and strengthen civil society.
The more diverse and interconnected European civil society structures become, the better equipped the new democracies will be for membership in the EU and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer various tasks of social solidarity to self-administered institutions and non-profit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economic it will be; and the better it will satisfy those social needs that central authorities cannot identify.
The social solidarity becomes more authentic when it is linked to people or their associations.
An authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest foundation for those forms of solidarity that only states can exercise.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy with its renunciation of European solidarity, which led to the capitulation of Munich.
This experience is still a powerful call to vigilance.
You have to stand up to the evil as soon as it appears, but it is not enough if only governments act.
For government policy grows out of the feelings of civil society, out of the people.
Concern for security is indeed a manifestation of societal solidarity.
The EU is working intensively on a new concept of its security policy.
It should be characterized by the ability to make quick decisions and quickly implement community decisions – reforms that the recent developments in Yugoslavia have shown to be necessary.
The intervention of NATO last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom as well as the interests of overall European security require intervention beyond EU borders.
Je stärker das Mandat zu einer solchen Aktion ist, um so besser.
Leider mag es Situationen geben, bei denen das UN-Mandat möglicherweise nicht kommt, obgleich eine Intervention im Interesse vieler Menschen, ganz Europas, ja sogar der menschlichen Zivilisation liegt.
Bis vor kurzem war Europa auf diese Alternative schlecht vorbereitet.
Es ist jetzt besser dafür gerüstet, zumindest psychologisch.
Diese psychologische Bereitschaft sollte genutzt werden, um Europas materielle und technische Bereitschaft zu befördern.
However, further measures are still needed in the field of preventive security, but even more is needed so that this security reflects the values of the expanded civil society of Europe.
Tens of thousands of human lives and enormous material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the beginning of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, one only acted hesitantly.
These failures were the result of various individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be watching the horror in Kosovo.
Europe cannot be dependent on the USA forever, especially not when it comes to European problems.
It must be able to agree on its own solutions.
It is unimaginable that the EU can exist as a respectable part of the world order if it proves to be unable to agree on means and ways to protect human rights, not only on its territory but also in areas that may join it one day.
Such an EU expansion is only conceivable if it progresses hand in hand with a courageous reform of EU institutions.
I am hopeful that the government conference on institutional reform will submit practicable proposals for the progress of the union.
But I consider this the beginning of a process that will take decades and should be led by a lasting effort to accelerate and make EU decision-making more transparent.
A related point with the institutional reform is the question of how to give smaller states the certainty that they are not simply outvoted by the larger ones, while still properly considering the size of the individual states.
A possibility lies in the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber are not elected directly, but elected by the parliaments of the member states from their own ranks.
The first chamber of the EU – i.e. the current parliament – would thus reflect the size of the individual member states, the second chamber would, with the same number of representatives for each state, increase equality.
Sometime earlier or later, these changes will require the EU to have a clear, understandable constitution – a text that all European children could learn.
A constitution of this kind requires two parts.
Part one would define the rights and duties, the underlying values, and the significance and goals of integration for both European citizens and the states.
Part two would describe the central EU institutions, their principal powers and their relationships with each other.
Such a constitutional law would not mean an automatic transformation of the current Union into a federal super-state, which is feared by Eurosceptics.
However, it would help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, to understand it better, to see the importance of the EU for their lives, and, as a result, to identify with it.
